{"id":"2301.00121","submitter":"Paul M. Terwilliger","authors":"Paul Terwilliger and Arjana \\v{Z}itnik","title":"Circular bidiagonal pairs","comments":"30 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.QA math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A square matrix is said to be circular bidiagonal whenever (i) each nonzero\nentry is on the diagonal, or the subdiagonal, or in the top-right corner; (ii)\neach subdiagonal entry is nonzero, and the entry in the top-right corner is\nnonzero. Let $\\mathbb F$ denote a field, and let $V$ denote a nonzero\nfinite-dimensional vector space over $\\mathbb F$. We consider an ordered pair\nof $\\mathbb F$-linear maps $A: V \\to V$ and $A^*: V \\to V$ that satisfy the\nfollowing two conditions: (i) there exists a basis for $V$ with respect to\nwhich the matrix representing $A$ is circular bidiagonal and the matrix\nrepresenting $A^*$ is diagonal; (ii) there exists a basis for $V$ with respect\nto which the matrix representing $A^*$ is circular bidiagonal and the matrix\nrepresenting $A$ is diagonal. We call such a pair a circular bidiagonal pair on\n$V$. We classify the circular bidiagonal pairs up to affine equivalence. There\nare two infinite families of solutions, which we describe in detail.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 31 Dec 2022 04:41:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-03"}
